  "texts": [
    "ThenF # C k (T) = C k (F # T).",
    "Properties of Lipschitz maps and their determinantsIf f: R d → R is Lispchitz, then by Rademacher's theorem its Frechét differetial Df (x) exists for almost every x ∈ R d. If E ⊂ R d and f: E → R is Lipschitz, then there is a Lipschitz extension f: R d → R of f. Moreover, at almost every point of E, f is Frechét differetible with the differential only dependending on f. Thus, if we let Df (x) be the Frechét differential at x of any Lipschitz extension of f, then Df (x) is well defined almost everywhere in E.If π: E → R d is Lipschitz, then the differential is identified with the matrix Dπ(x) = ( ∂π j ∂e i (x)) d i,j=1.Recall the basic inequality| det Dπ(x)| ≤ d j=1 ∥Dπ j (x)∥,whenever the left side is well defined, where on the right hand side the norm is the dual norm of (R d) *.",
    "In particular, we have∥det Dπ∥ L ∞ (E) ≤ d j=1Lip(π j).",
    "(2.2) Suppose π 1,..., π k: E → R and x ∈ E is such that Dπ j (x) exists for all j ∈ {1,..., k}.",
    "Recall that dπ j (x) = Dπ j (x)."
  ]
